Exceptions vs. Errors

Exception
 → Problem caused by or related to the program

Error
 → Problem outside of the program…
 → System-level issue
 → Something went wrong with the JVM

Important Syntax:
 try {}                                                → its like void in which it runs mainly
 catch (Exception e)                                   → if it catches an error this runs
 finally {}                                            → this always run mainly (This closes the 'try' like how we close scanner)
 System.exit(1)                                        → stops the entire program with an error, not just a class or main with an error. (I DONT REALLY KNOW HOW THIS WORK)
 System.exit(0)                                        → stops the entire program normally, not just a class or main. (I DONT REALLY KNOW HOW THIS WORK)
 throw                                                 → throws/creates an exception or error
 do                                                    → followed up by while, do runs first and then check the while loop at the end in order to continue or not.
 .getMessage()                                         → gets the error message
 .printStackTrace()                                    → prints where the error happened in the code
 .getClass()                                           → gets the type of exception
 .toString()                                           → returns the exception type + message combined

HONORABLE MENTIONS:
    - most custom exceptions are made by using an import called Throwable
    - Dividing any number with 0 as a double will return "Infinity"